          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are the 5 methods of transfer pricing?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The five prescribed methods are comparable uncontrolled price, resale price, cost plus, profit split and transactional net margin, with a sixth other method allowed under Rule 10AB. For an Indian development centre billing its overseas parent, the transactional net margin method is used most often, benchmarking operating profit on operating cost against comparable independent software companies."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between benchmarking and using the safe harbour rules?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Benchmarking searches a database for comparable companies and defends the margin actually earned, while the safe harbour rules let the taxpayer simply declare a minimum operating margin notified under Rule 10TD and avoid a transfer pricing audit on that transaction. Safe harbour is elected in Form 3CEFA and generally requires a higher margin than a benchmarking study would support."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Which transfer pricing filings apply to an Indian IT services company?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "An accountant's report in Form 3CEB is mandatory under Section 92E for any international transaction with an associated enterprise, regardless of value, and it is filed by 31 October of the assessment year. Contemporaneous documentation under Rule 10D is required once transactions exceed Rs 1 crore, and larger groups additionally file the master file in Form 3CEAA."
          }
        }
